Continuous Probability

Chapter 6

Section 6.1 through Section 6.3

Continuous Probability

Thus far have studied distributions with finite or countably infinite support.

Consider studying a continuous random variable that takes on an uncountable, continuum, of outcomes.

Example.

Let \( \small X \) be the reaction time in seconds to a given stimulus.

  • Theoretically, the possible outcomes are all positive real values.
  • In practice, we will observe rounded values (rounded to milliseconds).

Need a new type of function to properly understand continuous random variables.

Cumulative Distribution Function

Definition.

The cumulative distribution function or cdf of a random variable \( \small X \) is denoted by \( \small F_X(x) \) and given by

\[ F_X(x) = P(X \leq x) \quad \text{ for all real values x} \]

Note.

This definition is for every random variable, not just continuous!

Discrete cdf Example

Let \( \small X \sim HyperG(N = 10, r = 4, n = 3) \). Then,

\[ p(x) = \frac{{4 \choose x}{6 \choose 3-x}}{{10 \choose 3}} \quad \text{ for } x = 0, 1, 2, 3 \]

Notice this is a case where \( x_{max} < r \), another unique case for the HyperG distribution.

We can study this distribution with a table. Here I give three rows, the first representing the observed outcome \( \small x \). The second shows the values of the pmf, or the probability of observing the values \( \small x \). Remember this is a discrete case as we have studied, so the probabilities are given by the pmf. The third row accumulates the probabilities as \( \small x \) increases; this gives us the cumulative probabilities for \( \small X \), denoted \( \small F_X(x) \).

Notice the cdf gives the sum of all probabilities up to an included the observed \( \small x \). For discrete we find this with

\[ F_X(2) = P(X \leq 2) = p(0) + p(1) + p(2) = \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{2} + \frac{3}{10} = \frac{29}{30} \]

Discrete cdf Example Continued

Notice that we find the CDF by finding the probabilities accumulated up to and including \( \small x \).

For discrete distributions this created steps. Here is the cdf as a piecewise function.

\[ F_X(x) = \large \begin{cases} 0 &\quad x < 0 \\ \frac{5}{30} &\quad 0 \leq x < 1 \\ \frac{20}{30} &\quad 1 \leq x < 2 \\ \frac{29}{30} &\quad 2 \leq x < 3 \\ 1 &\quad x \geq 4 \end{cases} \]

Notice that the equalities are placed such that the probabilities 'jumps' as we reach the next observable outcome. This can be graphed.

CDF Properties

There are key properties that must hold for a function to be considered a cdf.

Properties of a cdf:

(1)

\[ \lim\limits_{x \to -\infty} F_X(x) = 0 \]

(2)

\[ \lim\limits_{x \to \infty} F_X(x) = 1 \]

(3)

\( \small F_X(x) \) is non-decreasing as a function of \( \small x \).

  • If \( \small x_1 < x_2 \), then \( \small F(x_1) \leq F(x_2) \).

(1)

\( \small F_X(x) \) is right-continuous

\[ \lim\limits_{x \to a^+} F_X(x) = F(a^+) = F(a) \]

Continuous Random Variable

Definition.

\( \small X \) is a continuous random variable if the cumulative distribution function of \( \small X \), \( \small F(x) \), is continuous for all real values \( \small x \).

Example of a Continuous Random Variable

Let \( \small X \) be a random variable with the cdf

\[ F_X(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \quad x < 0 \\ x & \quad 0 \leq x < 1 \\ 1 & \quad x \geq 1 \end{cases} \]

\( \small F(x) \) is continuous for all real values of \( \small x \), thus the random variable \( \small X \) is continuous.

Note.

For continuous random variables there are no jump-points (steps) in the cdf.

Note.

For a continuous random variable \( \small P(X = x_0) = 0 \) for any real valued number \( \small x_0 \).

Example Continued

\[ F_X(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \quad x < 0 \\ x & \quad 0 \leq x < 1 \\ 1 & \quad x \geq 1 \end{cases} \]

Probability is not associated with a number, such as in the discrete case. For continuous random variables, we associate probaility with an interval.

Probability \( \small X \) is less than or equal to 0.75

\[ P(X \leq 0.75) = F_X(0.75) = 0.75 \]

This is equivalent to fidning \( \small P(x \in (-\infty, 0.75]) \)

Probability \( \small X \) is between 1/9 and 9/8

\[ P(1/3 \leq X \leq 9/8) = F_X(9/8) - F_X(1/3) = 1 - 1/3 = 2/3 \]

Probability density function (pmf)

Definition.

For a continuous random variable, \( \small X \), the probability density function (pdf) of \( \small X \) is denoted \( \small f_X(x) \) and given by

\[ f_X(x) = \frac{d}{dx}F_X(x) = F^{'}_X(x) \]

provided that the derivative exists.

Note.

Baesd on the definitions of \( \small F_X(x) \) and \( \small f_X(x) \), we have that

\[ F_X(x) = \int\limits_{-\infty}^{x}f_X(x)dx = P(X \leq x) \]

The probability of a continuous random variable is associated with the area under the curve.

Return to Example

CDF

\[ F_X(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \quad x < 0 \\ x & \quad 0 \leq x < 1 \\ 1 & \quad x \geq 1 \end{cases} \]

PDF

\[ f_X(x) = F^{'}_X(x) = \begin{cases} 0 & \quad x < 0 \\ 1 & \quad 0 \leq x < 1 \\ 0 & \quad x \geq 1 \end{cases} \]

Properties of a pdf

What properties must a function \( \small f_X(x) \) have to be the pdf of a continuous random variable, \( \small X \)?

(1)

\( \small F_X(x) \) is non-decreasing, thus \( \small f_X(x) \) must be non-negative.

(2)

Because \( \small \lim\limits_{x\to\infty} F_X(x) = 1 \), thus \( \small f_X(x) \) must integrate to \( \small 1 \).

This gives us important results that relate back to our probability axioms.

Probability density function

Result.

If \( \small f(x) \) is the pdf of a continuous random variable, \( \small X \), then

(1)

\[ f(x) \geq 0 \text{ for any real value }x \]

(2)

\[ \int\limits_{-\infty}^{x}f(x)dx = 1 \]

Note.

This extends our axioms to continuous random variables.

Probability from a pdf

Result.

For a continuous random variable, \( \small X \), with pdf, \( \small f(x) \), and \( \small a \leq b \),

\[ \begin{aligned} P(a \leq X \leq b) &= F(b) - F(a) \\ &= \int\limits_{-\infty}^{b}f(x)dx - \int\limits_{-\infty}^{a}f(x)dx\\ \therefore P(a \leq X \leq b) &= \int\limits_{a}^{b}f(x)dx \end{aligned} \]

Note. The pdf does not give probabilities. Probability is found by integrating the pdf.
